  "prompt": "Is using \"hairs\" instead of \"hair\" grammatically incorrect?",
  "response": "Generally, \"hair\" is used as an uncountable noun when referring to the entire body of hair on a person's head or body. However, \"hairs\" can be grammatically correct in specific contexts:\n\n1. When referring to individual strands of hair (e.g., \"There are a few gray hairs on his head\")\n2. In scientific or precise descriptions\n3. When counting specific hairs\n\nIn most everyday speech and writing, \"hair\" is the preferred form. Using \"hairs\" as a general plural is usually considered incorrect.",
